{"title_page": "Department of Industry (New South Wales)", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox Government agency\n|agency_name   = NSW Department of Industry\n|type          = Department\n|nativename    = \n|nativename_a  = \n|nativename_r  = \n|logo          = \n|logo_width    = 270px\n|logo_caption  = \n|seal          = \n|seal_width    = \n|seal_caption  = \n|picture       = \n|picture_width = \n|picture_caption = \n|formed        = 1 July 2015\n|preceding1    = Department of Trade and Investment, Regional Infrastructure and Services\n|preceding2    = \n|dissolved     = {{enddate|2019|07|01|df=y}}\n|superseding   = [[Department of Planning, Industry and Environment]]\n|jurisdiction  = [[New South Wales]]\n|headquarters  = \n|region_code   = AU-NSW\n|coordinates   = \n|employees     = \n|budget        = \n|minister1_name  = '''Hon. [[John Barilaro]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS|sep=,|MP}}'''\n|minister1_pfo   = <br/>[[Deputy Premier of New South Wales|Deputy Premier]], [[Minister for Regional NSW, Skills and Small Business (New South Wales)#Skills|Minister for Skills]] and [[Minister for Regional NSW, Skills and Small Business (New South Wales)#Small Business|Minister for Small Business]]\n|minister2_name  = '''Hon. [[Niall Blair]] {{small|[[New South Wales Legislative Council|MLC]]}}'''\n|minister2_pfo   = <br/>[[Minister for Primary Industries, Lands and Water (New South Wales)#Primary Industries|Minister for Primary Industries]], [[Minister for Primary Industries, Lands and Water (New South Wales)#Regional Water|Minister for Regional Water]] and [[Minister for Trade and Industry (New South Wales)#Trade and Industry|Minister for Trade and Industry]]\n|minister3_name  = '''Hon. [[Paul Toole]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS|sep=,|MP}}'''\n|minister3_pfo   =<br/>[[Minister for Primary Industries, Lands and Water (New South Wales)#Lands and Forestry|Minister for Lands and Forestry]] and [[Minister for Primary Industries, Lands and Water (New South Wales)#Racing|Minister for Racing]]\n|minister4_name  = '''Hon. [[Stuart Ayres]]  {{small|[[ Member of parliament#Australia|MP]]}}'''\n|minister4_pfo   = <br/>[[ Minister for Sport (New South Wales)|Minister for Sport]]\n|minister5_name  = '''Hon. [[Adam Marshall]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS|sep=,|MP}}'''\n|minister5_pfo   = <br/>[[Minister for Trade and Industry (New South Wales)#Tourism and Major Events|Minister for Tourism and Major Events]] and [[Minister for Regional NSW, Skills and Small Business (New South Wales)#Assistant minister|Assistant minister for Skills]]\n|chief1_name     = Simon Draper\n|chief1_position = <br/>[[Departmental secretary|Secretary]]\n|chief2_name     = \n|chief2_position = \n|agency_type   =\n|parent_agency = \n|child5_agency = \n|website       = {{URL|http://www.industry.nsw.gov.au/}} \n|footnotes     = \n|chief3_name=|chief3_position=|chief4_name=|chief4_position=|chief5_name=|chief5_position=|chief6_name=|chief6_position=|chief7_name=|chief7_position=|chief8_name=|chief8_position=|chief9_name=|chief9_position=|parent_department=}}\nThe '''New South Wales Department of Industry''', a former [[Government department|department]] of the [[New South Wales Government]], from 2015 until 2019 was to lead the state government\u2019s contribution to making NSW a prosperous state, creating the conditions for NSW to be a place where people want to live and work and businesses choose to invest and grow.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.industry.nsw.gov.au/about|title=About us|website=NSW Department of Industry|language=en|access-date=2018-11-04}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[2019 New South Wales state election|2019 state election]] the department was abolished and most of its functions were merged with the [[Department of Planning and Environment (New South Wales)|Department of Planning and Environment]] to form the [[Department of Planning, Industry and Environment]], with effect from 1 July 2019. Both the Department of Industry and the Department of Planning and Environment were abolished on the same day.<ref name=\"gazette-20190402admin\">{{Gazette NSW |title=Administrative Arrangements (Administrative Changes\u2014Public Service Agencies) Order 2019 [NSW] |issue=159 |page=7-8 |date=2 April 2019 |url=https://www.legislation.nsw.gov.au/regulations/2019-159.pdf |access-date=4 April 2019 |via= }}</ref>\n\n== Structure ==\nUp until its 2019 abolition, the department was the lead agency in the Industry cluster, led by the [[Departmental secretary|secretary]], at the time, Simon Draper. \n\n===Ministers===\nThe department was responsible to the cluster\u2019s five portfolio ministers: at the time of its abolition, the [[Minister for Regional NSW, Skills and Small Business (New South Wales)#Skills|Minister for Skills]], and [[Minister for Regional NSW, Skills and Small Business (New South Wales)#Small%20Business|Minister for Small Business]], the Hon John Barilaro MP who also served as the Deputy Premier; the [[Minister for Primary Industries, Lands and Water (New South Wales)#Primary%20Industries|Minister for Primary Industries]], [[Minister for Primary Industries, Lands and Water (New South Wales)#Regional%20Water|Minister for Regional Water]], and [[Minister for Trade and Industry (New South Wales)#Trade%20and%20Industry|Minister for Trade and Industry]], the Hon Niall Blair MLC who also served as the coordinating minister of the industry cluster; the [[Minister for Primary Industries, Lands and Water (New South Wales)#Lands%20and%20Forestry|Minister for Lands and Forestry]], and [[Minister for Primary Industries, Lands and Water (New South Wales)#Racing|Minister for Racing]], the Hon Paul Toole MP; the [[Minister for Sport (New South Wales)|Minister for Sport]], the Hon Stuart Ayres MP; the [[Minister for Trade and Industry (New South Wales)#Tourism%20and%20Major%20Events|Minister for Tourism and Major Events]], and [[Minister for Regional NSW, Skills and Small Business (New South Wales)#Assistant%20minister|Assistant Minister for Skills]], the Hon Adam Marshall MP.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dpc.nsw.gov.au/assets/dpc-nsw-gov-au/files/Programs-and-Services/Governance/58d7579fbb/Governance_Arrangements_Chart.pdf|title=Governance Arrangements Chart|date=2018-07-01}}</ref> All ministers were ultimately responsible to the [[Parliament of New South Wales]].\n\n===Operational divisions===\nThe department had four operational areas delivering to the citizens of NSW and a single central division\u2014Corporate Service Partners\u2014providing departmental services and coordination across operational and strategic functions. \n\nThe four operational divisions were:\n\n* Skills and Economic Development\n* NSW Department of Primary Industries\n* Liquor, Gaming and Racing\n* Lands and Water.\n\nAlso, the NSW Chief Scientist and Engineer, the NSW Small Business Commissioner, the Land & Water Commissioner, and the Chief Audit Executive reported directly to the secretary.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Priorities==\nThe department\u2019s Corporate Plan 2015\u201319 set out its direction and focus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.industry.nsw.gov.au/about/our-business/our-priorities|title=Our corporate plan|website=NSW Department of Industry|language=en|access-date=2018-11-04}}</ref> It articulated the department\u2019s vision, purpose and values, and was driven by seven strategic priorities: \n\n* sustaining the conditions for economic development\n* innovation in primary industries to improve resilience and boost productivity\n* support to increase jobs and investment in NSW\n* skills development programs for employment\n* sustainable use and access to natural resources\n* risks managed for natural resources, farming and food\n* foster a vibrant and valued sport and active recreation sector.\n\nThe department\u2019s corporate plan underpinned the delivery of the NSW State Priorities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nsw.gov.au/improving-nsw/premiers-priorities/|title=NSW Government Premier's Priorities|website=NSW Government|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-11-04}}</ref>\n\n==Agencies==\nThe Department of Industry was the lead agency in the NSW Industry Cluster, which, up until its 2019 abolition, included the following agencies, state-owned corporations and statutory bodies:<ref name=\":0\" /> <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.industry.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0015/122415/NSW-Department-of-Industry-organisational-chart.pdf|title=NSW Industry Cluster|date=2018-05-21}}</ref>\n\n* Executive agencies: Local Land Services, Destination NSW, Office of Sport, and the NSW Institute of Sport\n* State-owned corporations: Forestry Corporation of NSW, and WaterNSW. \n* Cemeteries & Crematoria NSW\n* Combat Sports Authority of NSW\n* Dams Safety Committee\n* Dumaresq\u2013Barwon Border Rivers Commission\n* Fisheries Scientific Committee\n* Greyhound Racing NSW\n* Greyhound Welfare & Integrity Commission\n* Harness Racing NSW\n* Independent Liquor & Gaming Authority\n* Innovation and Productivity Council\n* Marine Estate Management Authority\n* NSW Rural Assistance Authority\n* NSW Skills Board\n* Racing NSW\n* Regional Sporting Venues Authority\n* Rice Marketing Board\n* Snowy Scientific Committee\n* State Sporting Venues Authority\n* Sydney Cricket Ground and Sports Trust\n* Sydney Olympic Park Authority\n* TAFE Commission\n* Venues NSW\n* Veterinary Practitioners Board\n* Wild Dog Destruction Board\n* Wine Grapes Marketing Board\n\n==History==\nThe Department of Industry, known as Department of Industry, Skills and Regional Development between 2015 and 2017, was formed on 1 July 2015 following the [[2015 New South Wales state election|2015 state election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://records-primo.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/primo-explore/fulldisplay?context=L&vid=61SRA&docid=ORGANISATIONS1006408|title=AGY-6946 Department of Industry, Skills and Regional Development (2015-2017) / Department of Industry (2017- )|website=NSW State Archives & Records|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> The predecessor industry departments of Department of Industry were:\n*Department of Industry and Investment (2009-2011),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://records-primo.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/primo-explore/fulldisplay?context=L&vid=61SRA&docid=ORGANISATIONS1005787|title=AGY-6325 Department of Industry and Investment (2009-2011) Department of Trade and Investment, Regional Infrastructure and Services (2011-2015)|website=NSW State Archives & Records|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> branded as Industry & Investment NSW<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.industry.nsw.gov.au/|title=Welcome|website=Industry & Investment NSW|date=June 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100609014126/http://www.industry.nsw.gov.au/|archivedate=9 June 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*Department of Trade and Investment, Regional Infrastructure and Services (2011-2015), branded as NSW Trade & Investment<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trade.nsw.gov.au/about/who-we-are|title=Who we are|website=Department of Trade and Investment, Regional Infrastructure and Services|date=June 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120603005935/http://www.trade.nsw.gov.au/about/who-we-are|archivedate=3 June 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*Department of Industry, Skills and Regional Development (2015-2017)\n\nThe Department of Industry was replaced by the [[Department of Planning, Industry and Environment]] in July 2019.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.industry.nsw.gov.au NSW Department of Industry] (www.industry.nsw.gov.au) webpage\n* [http://www.dpi.nsw.gov.au NSW Department of Primary Industries] (www.dpi.nsw.gov.au) webpage \n* [http://www.industry.nsw.gov.au/about/our-business/our-publications-and-websites/websites NSW Government websites aligned with the department and its related authorities, boards, institutions and corporations] (www.industry.nsw.gov.au/about/our-business/our-publications-and-websites/websites)\n{{New South Wales Government Departments}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct government departments of New South Wales|Industry]]\n[[Category:Economy of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:2015 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:2019 disestablishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Government agencies disestablished in 2019]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 2015]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox Government agency\n|agency_name   = NSW Department of Industry\n|type          = Department\n|nativename    = \n|nativename_a  = \n|nativename_r  = \n|logo          = \n|logo_width    = 270px\n|logo_caption  = \n|seal          = \n|seal_width    = \n|seal_caption  = \n|picture       = \n|picture_width = \n|picture_caption = \n|formed        = 1 July 2015\n|preceding1    = Department of Trade and Investment, Regional Infrastructure and Services\n|preceding2    = \n|dissolved     = {{enddate|2019|07|01|df=y}}\n|superseding   = [[Department of Planning, Industry and Environment]]\n|jurisdiction  = [[New South Wales]]\n|headquarters  = \n|region_code   = AU-NSW\n|coordinates   = \n|employees     = \n|budget        = \n|minister1_name  = '''Hon. [[John Barilaro]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS|sep=,|MP}}'''\n|minister1_pfo   = <br/>[[Deputy Premier of New South Wales|Deputy Premier]], [[Minister for Regional NSW, Skills and Small Business (New South Wales)#Skills|Minister for Skills]] and [[Minister for Regional NSW, Skills and Small Business (New South Wales)#Small Business|Minister for Small Business]]\n|minister2_name  = '''Hon. [[Niall Blair]] {{small|[[New South Wales Legislative Council|MLC]]}}'''\n|minister2_pfo   = <br/>[[Minister for Primary Industries, Lands and Water (New South Wales)#Primary Industries|Minister for Primary Industries]], [[Minister for Primary Industries, Lands and Water (New South Wales)#Regional Water|Minister for Regional Water]] and [[Minister for Trade and Industry (New South Wales)#Trade and Industry|Minister for Trade and Industry]]\n|minister3_name  = '''Hon. [[Paul Toole]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS|sep=,|MP}}'''\n|minister3_pfo   =<br/>[[Minister for Primary Industries, Lands and Water (New South Wales)#Lands and Forestry|Minister for Lands and Forestry]] and [[Minister for Primary Industries, Lands and Water (New South Wales)#Racing|Minister for Racing]]\n|minister4_name  = '''Hon. [[Stuart Ayres]]  {{small|[[ Member of parliament#Australia|MP]]}}'''\n|minister4_pfo   = <br/>[[ Minister for Sport (New South Wales)|Minister for Sport]]\n|minister5_name  = '''Hon. [[Adam Marshall]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS|sep=,|MP}}'''\n|minister5_pfo   = <br/>[[Minister for Trade and Industry (New South Wales)#Tourism and Major Events|Minister for Tourism and Major Events]] and [[Minister for Regional NSW, Skills and Small Business (New South Wales)#Assistant minister|Assistant minister for Skills]]\n|chief1_name     = Simon Draper\n|chief1_position = <br/>[[Departmental secretary|Secretary]]\n|chief2_name     = \n|chief2_position = \n|agency_type   =\n|parent_agency = \n|child5_agency = \n|website       = {{URL|http://www.industry.nsw.gov.au/}} \n|footnotes     = \n|chief3_name=|chief3_position=|chief4_name=|chief4_position=|chief5_name=|chief5_position=|chief6_name=|chief6_position=|chief7_name=|chief7_position=|chief8_name=|chief8_position=|chief9_name=|chief9_position=|parent_department=}}\nThe '''New South Wales Department of Industry''', a former [[Government department|department]] of the [[New South Wales Government]], from 2015 until 2019 was to lead the state government\u2019s contribution to making NSW a prosperous state, creating the conditions for NSW to be a place where people want to live and work and businesses choose to invest and grow.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.industry.nsw.gov.au/about|title=About us|website=NSW Department of Industry|language=en|access-date=2018-11-04}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[2019 New South Wales state election|2019 state election]] the department was abolished and most of its functions were merged with the [[Department of Planning and Environment (New South Wales)|Department of Planning and Environment]] to form the [[Department of Planning, Industry and Environment]], with effect from 1 July 2019. Both the Department of Industry and the Department of Planning and Environment were abolished on the same day.<ref name=\"gazette-20190402admin\">{{Gazette NSW |title=Administrative Arrangements (Administrative Changes\u2014Public Service Agencies) Order 2019 [NSW] |issue=159 |page=7-8 |date=2 April 2019 |url=https://www.legislation.nsw.gov.au/regulations/2019-159.pdf |access-date=4 April 2019 |via= }}</ref>\n\n== Structure ==\nUp until its 2019 abolition, the department was the lead agency in the Industry cluster, led by the [[Departmental secretary|secretary]], at the time, Simon Draper. \n\n===Ministers===\nThe department was responsible to the cluster\u2019s five portfolio ministers: at the time of its abolition, the [[Minister for Regional NSW, Skills and Small Business (New South Wales)#Skills|Minister for Skills]], and [[Minister for Regional NSW, Skills and Small Business (New South Wales)#Small%20Business|Minister for Small Business]], the Hon John Barilaro MP who also served as the Deputy Premier; the [[Minister for Primary Industries, Lands and Water (New South Wales)#Primary%20Industries|Minister for Primary Industries]], [[Minister for Primary Industries, Lands and Water (New South Wales)#Regional%20Water|Minister for Regional Water]], and [[Minister for Trade and Industry (New South Wales)#Trade%20and%20Industry|Minister for Trade and Industry]], the Hon Niall Blair MLC who also served as the coordinating minister of the industry cluster; the [[Minister for Primary Industries, Lands and Water (New South Wales)#Lands%20and%20Forestry|Minister for Lands and Forestry]], and [[Minister for Primary Industries, Lands and Water (New South Wales)#Racing|Minister for Racing]], the Hon Paul Toole MP; the [[Minister for Sport (New South Wales)|Minister for Sport]], the Hon Stuart Ayres MP; the [[Minister for Trade and Industry (New South Wales)#Tourism%20and%20Major%20Events|Minister for Tourism and Major Events]], and [[Minister for Regional NSW, Skills and Small Business (New South Wales)#Assistant%20minister|Assistant Minister for Skills]], the Hon Adam Marshall MP.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dpc.nsw.gov.au/assets/dpc-nsw-gov-au/files/Programs-and-Services/Governance/58d7579fbb/Governance_Arrangements_Chart.pdf|title=Governance Arrangements Chart|date=2018-07-01}}</ref> All ministers were ultimately responsible to the [[Parliament of New South Wales]].\n\n===Operational divisions===\nThe department had four operational areas delivering to the citizens of NSW and a single central division\u2014Corporate Service Partners\u2014providing departmental services and coordination across operational and strategic functions. \n\nThe four operational divisions were:\n\n* Skills and Economic Development\n* NSW Department of Primary Industries\n* Liquor, Gaming and Racing\n* Lands and Water.\n\nAlso, the NSW Chief Scientist and Engineer, the NSW Small Business Commissioner, the Land & Water Commissioner, and the Chief Audit Executive reported directly to the secretary.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Priorities==\nThe department\u2019s Corporate Plan 2015\u201319 set out its direction and focus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.industry.nsw.gov.au/about/our-business/our-priorities|title=Our corporate plan|website=NSW Department of Industry|language=en|access-date=2018-11-04}}</ref> It articulated the department\u2019s vision, purpose and values, and was driven by seven strategic priorities: \n\n* sustaining the conditions for economic development\n* innovation in primary industries to improve resilience and boost productivity\n* support to increase jobs and investment in NSW\n* skills development programs for employment\n* sustainable use and access to natural resources\n* risks managed for natural resources, farming and food\n* foster a vibrant and valued sport and active recreation sector.\n\nThe department\u2019s corporate plan underpinned the delivery of the NSW State Priorities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nsw.gov.au/improving-nsw/premiers-priorities/|title=NSW Government Premier's Priorities|website=NSW Government|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-11-04}}</ref>\n\n==Agencies==\nThe Department of Industry was the lead agency in the NSW Industry Cluster, which, up until its 2019 abolition, included the following agencies, state-owned corporations and statutory bodies:<ref name=\":0\" /> <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.industry.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0015/122415/NSW-Department-of-Industry-organisational-chart.pdf|title=NSW Industry Cluster|date=2018-05-21}}</ref>\n\n* Executive agencies: Local Land Services, Destination NSW, Office of Sport, and the NSW Institute of Sport\n* State-owned corporations: Forestry Corporation of NSW, and WaterNSW. \n* Cemeteries & Crematoria NSW\n* Combat Sports Authority of NSW\n* Dams Safety Committee\n* Dumaresq\u2013Barwon Border Rivers Commission\n* Fisheries Scientific Committee\n* Greyhound Racing NSW\n* Greyhound Welfare & Integrity Commission\n* Harness Racing NSW\n* Independent Liquor & Gaming Authority\n* Innovation and Productivity Council\n* Marine Estate Management Authority\n* NSW Rural Assistance Authority\n* NSW Skills Board\n* Racing NSW\n* Regional Sporting Venues Authority\n* Rice Marketing Board\n* Snowy Scientific Committee\n* State Sporting Venues Authority\n* Sydney Cricket Ground and Sports Trust\n* Sydney Olympic Park Authority\n* TAFE Commission\n* Venues NSW\n* Veterinary Practitioners Board\n* Wild Dog Destruction Board\n* Wine Grapes Marketing Board\n\n==History==\nThe Department of Industry, known as Department of Industry, Skills and Regional Development between 2015 and 2017, was formed on 1 July 2015 following the [[2015 New South Wales state election|2015 state election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://records-primo.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/primo-explore/fulldisplay?context=L&vid=61SRA&docid=ORGANISATIONS1006408|title=AGY-6946 Department of Industry, Skills and Regional Development (2015-2017) / Department of Industry (2017- )|website=NSW State Archives & Records|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> The predecessor industry departments of Department of Industry were:\n*Department of Industry and Investment (2009-2011),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://records-primo.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/primo-explore/fulldisplay?context=L&vid=61SRA&docid=ORGANISATIONS1005787|title=AGY-6325 Department of Industry and Investment (2009-2011) Department of Trade and Investment, Regional Infrastructure and Services (2011-2015)|website=NSW State Archives & Records|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> branded as Industry & Investment NSW<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.industry.nsw.gov.au/|title=Welcome|website=Industry & Investment NSW|date=June 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100609014126/http://www.industry.nsw.gov.au/|archivedate=9 June 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*Department of Trade and Investment, Regional Infrastructure and Services (2011-2015), branded as NSW Trade and Investment<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trade.nsw.gov.au/about/who-we-are|title=Who we are|website=Department of Trade and Investment, Regional Infrastructure and Services|date=June 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120603005935/http://www.trade.nsw.gov.au/about/who-we-are|archivedate=3 June 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*Department of Industry, Skills and Regional Development (2015-2017)\n\nThe Department of Industry was replaced by the [[Department of Planning, Industry and Environment]] in July 2019.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.industry.nsw.gov.au NSW Department of Industry] (www.industry.nsw.gov.au) webpage\n* [http://www.dpi.nsw.gov.au NSW Department of Primary Industries] (www.dpi.nsw.gov.au) webpage \n* [http://www.industry.nsw.gov.au/about/our-business/our-publications-and-websites/websites NSW Government websites aligned with the department and its related authorities, boards, institutions and corporations] (www.industry.nsw.gov.au/about/our-business/our-publications-and-websites/websites)\n{{New South Wales Government Departments}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct government departments of New South Wales|Industry]]\n[[Category:Economy of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:2015 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:2019 disestablishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Government agencies disestablished in 2019]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 2015]]\n", "name_user": "Marcnut1996", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Department_of_Industry_(New_South_Wales)"}
